The '''Plymouth Concord''', was a [[full-size car]], produced by [[Plymouth (automobile)|Plymouth]] between 1951 and 1952. It was Plymouth's least expensive model in its lineup, replacing the [[Plymouth Deluxe|Deluxe]].

== Models ==
This line of Plymouths was introduced in 1951 when "war demands nearly eliminated auto production and restricted access to key metals."<ref name="allpar-plymouth49-52">{{cite web|url= http://www.allpar.com/cars/plymouth/cranbrook.html |title=The Plymouth Cranbrook, Cambridge, and Concord cars, 1951-1954 |first=Jim |last=Benjaminson |work=Allpar |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> The body styles were unchanged from the previous year with the Concord available in a three-passenger business coupe, a fastback two-door sedan, or an all-metal two-door Suburban station wagon.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YgUKAQAAMAAJ&q=new+Plymouth+Concord+sedan+three+passenger+coupe |page=56 |title=Plymouth, 1946-1959 |first=James A. |last=Benjaminson |publisher=Motorbooks International |year=1994 |isbn=9780879388409 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> The Concord Series was available in a simple ''Deluxe'' trim level. For the new all-metal two-door Suburban station wagon, an additional ''[[Plymouth Savoy|Special Savoy]]'' trim level was available.<ref name="allpar-plymouth49-52"/> This upgrade included better upholstery, arm rests, assist straps, storage compartments, and chrome exterior window and belt line trim.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SX2pBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=Plymouth+Concord |page=74 |title=Plymouth wagons: includes Dodge-DeSoto-Chrysler, 1939-1954 |first=Don |last=Narus |publisher=New Albany Books |year=2013 |isbn=9781467559850 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> The business coupe featured cargo space behind the front bench seat.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=fVEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=new+Plymouth+Concord+sedan+three+passenger+coupe |pages=20–21 |title=How to select the car model that best suits your needs (Plymouth advertisement) |journal=Life |date=21 May 1951 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>

The 1952 model year included minor changes to medallions, [[hood ornament]], and script nameplates, but after the midyear an optional electric [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] unit (for speeds over 25&nbsp;mph) was added for the manual transmission (no automatic transmission was available).<ref name="allpar-plymouth49-52"/>

The Concord model line was dropped for 1953 and replaced by the Cambridge for the lowest trim level.<ref name="allpar-plymouth49-52"/>

== Name origin ==
[[Plymouth, Massachusetts]], was one of the first European settlements in North America and is a major city in the state. Two of Plymouth's model lines in the 1950s were named after towns in Massachusetts: [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] and [[Concord, Massachusetts|Concord]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Allpar |url= http://www.allpar.com/history/plymouth/plymouths-1949-1952.html |title=Plymouth cars of 1949 to 1952 |first=Lanny |last=Knutson |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>

The name "Concord", was later used by [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]] (AMC) for its line of compact cars (see: 1978-83 [[AMC Concord]]).

The name was resurrected by the Chrysler division after it bought out AMC on its full-size cars (see: 1993-2004 [[Chrysler Concorde]]), though it was spelled "Concord'''e'''".

